---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Morning Briefing - 07/10/26: Power Grab TX">
  <div class="post-page">
    <div class="post-content">
      <h1>⭐ Morning Briefing — Texas &amp; DFW AI Data Centers, Power Grid, Land Use</h1>
      <p class="briefing-subtitle">(Latest updates through July 10, 2026)</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>⚡ 1. Major Political &amp; Regulatory Shifts Affecting AI Data Centers</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Gov. Greg Abbott now publicly supports banning AI data centers in rural Texas, reversing his earlier pro-industry stance. He argues centers must bring their own power, water, and infrastructure and no longer receive tax breaks.</li>
        <li>Abbott's comments follow rising statewide opposition — 56% of Texans oppose data centers in their community.</li>
        <li>Texas Agriculture Commissioner Sid Miller is pushing for a special legislative session to halt expansion.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Signal:</strong> Political winds have shifted sharply. Expect new statewide restrictions in the 2027 legislative session.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏛️ 2. ERCOT &amp; Grid Reliability — New Rules + Serious Failures</h2>

      <h3>New mandatory grid ride-through rules</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The Texas Public Utility Commission approved rules requiring data centers to stay online during grid disturbances or face forced disconnection.</li>
        <li>Regulators warn that large AI centers (often &gt;1,000 MW) can destabilize the grid if they trip offline.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Multiple data centers failed ERCOT voltage tests</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Four large data center/crypto groups failed voltage ride-through tests, each capable of dropping &gt;5,000 MW instantly — equivalent to the load of Boston.</li>
        <li>ERCOT has recorded 26 abrupt disconnects since 2023, raising reliability concerns.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>ERCOT long-term warning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>ERCOT's latest forecast shows Texas could face an 8.3% power shortfall by summer 2027, worsening to 32.4% by 2029, driven heavily by data center load growth.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Signal:</strong> ERCOT is tightening interconnection rules; expect delays, mandatory upgrades, and stricter compliance for any new DFW or Texas data center project.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏗️ 3. New Construction, Land Deals &amp; Corporate Announcements (DFW + Texas)</h2>

      <h3>DFW / North Texas</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>DataBank Red Oak Campus (292 acres south of Dallas) secured $2B financing for a 480MW campus; first 180MW phase fully leased.</li>
        <li>Big Digital Energy acquired land for a 311MW campus outside DFW.</li>
        <li>Plans filed for a new 100,000 sq ft data center near Dallas (Royse City).</li>
        <li>Edged filed to develop a new Fort Worth data center, launching next year.</li>
        <li>EG AI launching a 2.5MW immersion-cooled facility in DFW.</li>
        <li>Core Scientific purchased land for a 285MW campus outside Dallas.</li>
        <li>Prometheus Hyperscale planning a 200MW Dallas campus.</li>
        <li>CyrusOne partnering with Constellation for a 760MW Texas campus.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Statewide</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Google investing $40B in Texas data centers (DFW → Amarillo corridor).</li>
        <li>Facebook/Meta spending $10B outside El Paso.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Signal:</strong> Despite political pushback, DFW remains the #1 global data center market (Cushman &amp; Wakefield 2026 ranking).</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏘️ 4. Zoning, Land Use &amp; Community Pushback (DFW Focus)</h2>

      <h3>Fort Worth</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Zoning Commission rejected new data center regulations (7–4 vote), citing insufficient detail.</li>
        <li>
          Proposed rules would:
          <ul>
            <li>Ban crypto mining</li>
            <li>Restrict data centers to industrial zones</li>
            <li>Require setbacks, lighting, landscaping standards</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>City Council considering a 90-day moratorium on new data center permits.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>North Texas suburbs</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Residents in North Richland Hills, Red Oak, Lavon, Granbury expressing strong opposition over noise, water use, and land impact.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Signal:</strong> Expect slower permitting, more community hearings, and stricter zoning in DFW cities.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🔌 5. Market &amp; Infrastructure Trends to Watch</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Texas interconnection queue hit 410GW, dominated by data center requests — 5× current grid capacity.</li>
        <li>Developers increasingly adopting power-first strategies (on-site generation, long-term PPAs, behind-the-meter solutions).</li>
        <li>West Texas emerging as a major AI infrastructure hub with 2.9GW under construction.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Signal:</strong> Power availability is now the primary gating factor for all Texas data center development.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>📌 6. What We Are Watching</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Fort Worth City Council vote on the 90-day moratorium.</li>
        <li>PUC + ERCOT enforcement of new ride-through rules — potential project delays.</li>
        <li>Legislative proposals for statewide restrictions in 2027.</li>
        <li>DFW land acquisition patterns (Red Oak, Royse City, Plano, Mansfield).</li>
        <li>Transmission expansion announcements — critical for 2027–2030 reliability.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="post-related">
        <h3>Related Pages</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/trackers">AI Data Center Tracker</a> — The full running, dated record of Texas AI data center developments.</li>
          <li><a href="/news">Latest News</a> — Updates on Texas energy, AI expansion, and infrastructure changes.</li>
          <li><a href="/stay-informed">Stay Informed</a> — Get alerts and updates about developments affecting Texas communities.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
